About This Project

In this project, I will explore the affects of three (3) different models and their effect on classificaiton: Softmax Regression, Support Vector Machine, and Random forest. After exploring the possible hyperparameters for each, I will choose the best and combine them to create an ensemble and analyze its performance against the individial models.

For these models, I will be working with a sleep disorder where I by trying to predict the label "sleep disorder." The dataset contains instances of people with describing features, such as bmi, stress level, blood preasure, etc

Eventually the Disorder will be converted to integer representations as follows: 1=None, 2 = Sleap Apnea, and 3=Insomnia

Pt. 1 Analysis:

Dataset Breakdown:

Our Dataset Consists of 374 instances. There are a total of 11 features that we will use in this order. I will have to do a lot of encoding due to some being categorical. The feature names are: Gender,Age,Occupation,Sleep Duration,Quality of Sleep,Physical Activity Level,Stress Level,BMI Category,Blood Pressure,Heart Rate,Daily Steps.

I have 1 label to predict, named "Sleep Disorder" We temporarily add this as the first feature of our dataset for our future data analyses. Sleep Disorder is converted to a class (1,2, or 3), it is not continuous.

Statistical Values:

All of our means have wildly different values. Optimally, this would not be the case. Despite this, the mean does often lie close to the 50th percentile.

Distributions:

Looking at eeach distribution, it is hard to find a single one that appears to follow a normal distribution, or anything other than random. The only two that appear meaningful in their distrubtions is the fact that there is about equal occurances of Males and Females, and that stress levels are almost equally distributed also. If I had to guess, these tests were not exact and rounding was often employed, considering that there are very tall columns and very short columns randomely in each plot.
Due to the presence of many outliers, the charts being skewed, and the ranges of values of each features, I will have to normalize the data. After searching my options, the robust scalers will likely be the best consdiering the randomness of teh distributions and the varying range of values of each feature.

One more thing to note is that we do not have an equal number of labels for each class. However, there are similar counts from class 2 and 3

Pt. 2: Analysis

Pearson Correlations:

Many of the PCC values are low, within the range of [-.5, .5]; however there are a few featurers with higher PCC values. These are: both Blood Pressures, Occupational Salesperson, and BMI category Overweight. Looks at the charts, there do appear to be some linear correlations with the features to the label. However it is also important to not that for some high PCC values, in this case occupational salesperson, there are very few instances of True for that feature, meaning outliers affect it more and could be creating an apparent correlation where there is none.

By Looking at the graphs, it validates the PCC value finding also. There are a few that likely have a linear correlations, such as the BMI_overweight; however, most do not. It should also be noted that most of the features do not appear to be random on the graph, meaning there is likely some non-linear relations of the features.

Pt. 3 Analysis:

Data Splitting:

Our data is split into three sets: training, validation, and testing based based on a chose 70/15/15 split. I chose this split per my own discretion. There are a resulting 262 instances of the training set, and 56 instances in both the validation and testing set

Data Normalization:
Due to the presence of many extreme outliers, an unknown distribution, skewed histograms, and very large ranges of values, I performed normalization using the scikit robust scaler which is for these scenarious. This does not gauruntee that the resulting values will be small. In this case, it performed pretty well though, with values now ranging between around [-2, 4] for each set. The slightly higher values for some features may end up resulting in slight bias in the SVM and Regression model for those features though though. Label Distributions:

Unfortunately, there is not an even number of sleep disorders in each set of data. In each set, the number of No sleep dirsorders is always greater than the disorder. And then the other two disorders- sleep apnea and insomnia are similar. Because each set has relatively equal porportions however, are training and validation set should give a pretty accurate representation of how the models perform. I just need to watch to see if the models are actually performing well overall, or they are just performing well on class 1 adn neglecting classes 2 and 3

#As we continue, we will make extensize use of each of these function. We just added them here to clean
#up our code and make it a lot more understandable, readable
from sklearn.metrics import precision_score, recall_score, accuracy_score, f1_score
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.svm import SVC
import numpy as np
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=UserWarning, module='sklearn')

#print accuracy, precision, recall,and f1 score
def print_score(y_val, veri_hat):
    print("Accuracy: ", accuracy_score(y_val, veri_hat ))
    print("Precision: ", precision_score(y_val, veri_hat, average='weighted'))
    print("Recall: ", recall_score(y_val, veri_hat, average='weighted'))
    print("F1 Score: ", f1_score(y_val, veri_hat, average='weighted'))

#explore a hyperparameter on a model and print its graph
def explore_parameter(hyperparams, model_choice="SVM", test_name = "parameter" , title = None, true_labels = False):
    #store each model results
    acc_sc, prec_sc, rec_sc, f1_sc = [], [], [], []


    #keep track of the best parameter in the current test_name
    best_val, best_accuracy = 0,0

    #explor each paramter
    for param in hyperparams: 

        if model_choice == "SVM": 
            model = SVC(**param)
        elif model_choice == "sr":
            model = LogisticRegression(**param)
        elif model_choice == "rf":
            model = RandomForestClassifier(**param)

        model.fit(X_train, y_train.ravel())

        veri_hat = model.predict(X_val)

        acc_sc.append(accuracy_score(y_val, veri_hat))
        prec_sc.append(precision_score(y_val, veri_hat, average='weighted'))
        rec_sc.append(recall_score(y_val, veri_hat, average='weighted'))
        f1_sc.append(f1_score(y_val, veri_hat, average='weighted'))

        if (acc_sc[-1] > best_accuracy): 
            best_accuracy = acc_sc[-1]
            best_val = param[test_name]

    n_iterations = range(len(hyperparams))
    plt.figure(figsize=(7, 5))
    plt.plot(n_iterations, acc_sc, label="Accuracy", color="#bb7438", marker="o", linestyle="--")
    plt.plot(n_iterations, prec_sc, label="Precision", color="#7f64b9", marker="s", linestyle="--")
    plt.plot(n_iterations, rec_sc, label="Recall", color="#72ac5c", marker="^", linestyle="--")
    plt.plot(n_iterations, f1_sc, label="F1", color="#b94b75", marker="o", linestyle="--")
    if title != None: plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(f"{test_name}")
    plt.ylabel("Score")
    if(true_labels):
        x_ticks = [p[test_name] for p in hyperparams] 
        plt.xticks(ticks= n_iterations, labels = x_ticks)
    else: plt.xticks(n_iterations[::len(hyperparams)//10])
    plt.legend()
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

    return best_val

Pt. 3.1 Analysis:

Softmax Regression: Choosing Hyperparameters

In order to choose the best hyperparameters, I sequentially chose a hyperparameter, and found its best value for performance based on accuracy on the validation set. Then, when finding the next hyperparemeter, I included the best hyperparameters that come before it when searching. Though, this gauruntees the best individual hyperparameter values, it does not neccessarily gauruntee us the best combination of hyperparameter values. However, it does save a lot of proccessing power as opposed to other methods and still gives us a decent model solution.

Hyperparameters Explored (sequentially):

C value, solver, max iterations

Pt. 4.2 Analysis:

Support Vector Machine: Choosing Hyperparameters

In order to choose the best hyperparameters, I sequentially chose a hyperparameter, and found its best value for performance based on accuracy. Then, when finding the next hyperparemeter, I included the best hyperparameters that come before it when searching. Though, this gauruntees the best individual hyperparameter values, it does not neccessarily gauruntee us the best combination of hyperparameter values.

One curious note is that this time, I tried to also use gridsearch. I could not test as many values due to the computation times; however made sure to include the manual hyperparameters we found. Despite this, its accuracy was lower. This is likely do to the cross validation not using our validation set, even though theoretically its accuracy should be the same, if not better then the hyperparamers we manually found. This also means that the gridsearch has less instances to use for training on each fold due to a portion being committed to validation.

Findings:

Of all of our Models, there was a four way tie (when rounding to 4 sig figs) based on validation accuracy. The tie was between: Support Vector Machine, Softmax Regression, Hard Voting, and the Stacked model. Becuase of this, I chose (purely based on personal preference) to choose as my model for testing. My logic was that it was simpler compared to the others and easier to understand, especially compared to the stacked model with had all three individual classifiers and still had the same validation accuracy. This also means it takes less resources.
